description: Black Camaros will always be in demand, and this 1970 Chevrolet Camaro definitely has the right look with its sleek, dark appearance. And it's more than just skin deep, too, with a great-running 350 under the hood, a classic black bucket seat interior, and a ton of potential to be the Camaro you've always dreamed of owning.

It's safe to say that we like the way this Camaro looks. A lot! It's got the right stance, the right color, and the overall look of the second-generation cars is quite aggressive.  That's especially true thanks to upgrades like the big block Corvette-style hood and Z/28-style full-width spoiler.  But that's not what first grabbed you attention.  Nope, it's the recent application of black paint that makes the lasting first impression.  There was enough investment here that it shines like a mirror.  In fact, the luster is so nice it rivals the brightwork on the bumpers and headlight surrounds.

The black interior has recently been re- finished to stock specs with a few nice upgrades.  It looks like midnight with the fresh carpeting, bucket seats, door panels, and smooth dash.  Your right hand will love the tall shifter, and your left one will never want to leave the Grant GT steering wheel.   The factory gauges are in good original condition and they're joined by an auxiliary trio to keep you completely informed about what's going on under the hood.  So with this one has an upgraded AM/FM/CD stereo with Bluetooth, we really know your favorite soundtrack happens when you twist the key and let this Camaro roar.

The smart-running 350 cubic inch V8 looks fresh in its bright Chevy Orange paint, and it was clearly built for combat. Set up with a Holley four-barrel carburetor and Edelbrock intake.  This enhanced powerplant makes a terrific sound out of the dual exhaust.  Best of all, you are in complete control of the powerband and its thunderous soundtrack thanks to the four-speed manual transmission.  This feeds a 10-bolt rear end running versatile 3.55 gears.  Out on the road, you're going to like the feeling that comes from great driving features like the front disc brakes and thick sway bar up front.  There's also a set of gorgeous SS wheels wearing proper Firestone Wide Oval tires for the perfect finishing touch on this muscle machine.

Super clean, very potent, totally sorted, and a modern looking dark side exterior, this is the kind of Camaro you would have built for yourself. The fact that it's also so nicely priced and available today is only icing on the cake. Call now!!!

description: For sale in our Denver showroom is a 1968 numbers matching red Chevrolet Camaro. The Chevrolet Camaro is an American automobile manufactured by Chevrolet, classified as a pony car and some versions also as a muscle car. It went on sale on September 29, 1966, for the 1967 model year and was designed as a competing model to the Ford Mustang. The car shared its platform and major components with the Pontiac Firebird, also introduced for 1967. Before any official announcement, reports began running during April 1965 within the automotive press that Chevrolet was preparing a competitor to the Ford Mustang, code-named Panther.This beautiful second owner car has been meticulously cared for its whole life, and garage kept only 68,576 original miles. In May of 2017 had a full tune up on the 327 V8 including: 4 barrel Carburetor rebuilt, new battery, new alternator, new distributor, new spark plugs, new distributor cap and rotor from HEI Ignition, new plug wires, new fuel lines, new trans filter, new air filter. She also has double bump heads, the original protecto plate, and breathable car cover. This low mileage beauty is a dream to drive. And would make a great addition to anyoneÃ¢??s collections. When you get behind the wheel of this two-owner gorgeous Camaro, it will take you back to the glory days. When gasoline was only .34 cents a gallon, and Apollo 8 made the first maned trip orbiting the moon. To view the car in greater detail, including an HD video and 100+ HD pictures please visit www.gatewayclassiccars.com or our Denver showroom. Call 303-872-4722 for more information.

description: A head-turning presence, custom A/C interior, and an enhanced 305 V8 under the hood â€“ this well-price and iconic 1968 Chevrolet Camaro only gets better the more you look at it!

Everyone can agree that the early Camaros were awesome-looking cars with their smooth looks and minimum of fussy ornamentation. That's why the first-generation Camaro is always in demand, and the design is the basis for the latest generation.  And this car really lets you understand the enthusiasm that makes it an icon.  It has the kind of terrific gloss and shine on a more recent application of 1968-correct Matador Red.  This kind of fiery paint will get you noticed from across a parking lot.  Plus, with upgrades like the cowl hood, blacked-out rear panel, and D80 full-width rear spoiler, this has one heck of a sporting attitude.  And while you're enjoying the brightwork on everything from the wraparound bumpers to the large 17-inch American Racing Torq Thrust wheel, don't forget to enjoy the details, too.  For example, behind the front wheels, you can see cool red calipers that match the paint.

The custom and sporty appearance continues once you open the door.  This is a factory black interior that has been given some great investments.  It starts with those modern Procar sports seats.  Not only do they nicely bridge the gap between the red exterior and black interior, but also these modern buckets hold you more secure than the factory units ever could.  And the modern comfort continues on the late-model center console.  There's great features like power steering and an AM/FM/CD stereo.  You even have ice-cold air conditioning to keep you cool in this classic.  But this Camaro is more than just a coddler.  Your heart will begin to race from the moment you grab the upgraded sports steering wheel in your right hand, and lay your left one on the B&M shifter.

Under the hood is plenty of show-worthy polished elements like the air topper, valve covers (w/bow ties), alternator, and pulleys.  But what will really get your enthusiast heart excited is that beneath the glamour is some serious substance.  The 305 cubic-inch V8 has been built with go-fast goodies such as an Edelbrock four-barrel carburetor, Edelbrock intake, and long tube headers that add power as they feed the rumbling dual exhaust.  This still has the correct Powerglide automatic transmission that's good for easy cruising when you want it, and powerful take-offs when it's time to drive fast.  In fact, this one has all the right performance upgrades, including Lakewood traction bars in the rear, upgraded disc brakes up front, and grippy modern tires at all four corners.
A great color scheme, the right luxury upgrades, and plenty of power for the streets â€“ this is total package first-gen Camaro for quite a nice price.  Don't miss out, call today!

HISTORY  The first-generation Camaro debuted in September 1966, for the 1967 model year, up to 1969 on a new rear-wheel drive GM F-body platform and was available as a two-door coupÃ© or convertible with 2+2 seating, and a choice of 230 cu in (3.8 L), 250 cu in (4.1 L) inline-6 or 302 cu in (4.9 L), 307 cu in (5.0 L), 327 cu in (5.4 L), 350 cu in (5.7 L), 396 cu in (6.5 L), 427 cu in (7.0 L) V8 powerplants. Concerned with the runaway success of the Ford Mustang, Chevrolet executives realized that their compact sporty car, the Corvair, would not be able to generate the sales volume of the Mustang due to its rear-engine design, as well as declining sales, partly due to the negative publicity from Ralph Nader's book, Unsafe at Any Speed. Therefore, the Camaro was touted as having the same conventional rear-drive, front-engine configuration as the Mustang and Chevy II Nova. In addition, the Camaro was designed to fit a variety of power plants in the engine bay. The first-generation Camaro lasted until the 1969 model year and eventually inspired the design of the new retro fifth-generation Camaro. description: This is the birth of a legend.  The 1967 Camaro launched the icon, so it's great to see it shining brightly in its original interesting color combo.  It might even have its original V8, too!  But as you pour through the details on this coupe, it's the subtle upgrades that make it irresistible.

It's hard to resist a Camaro in its original shade of Marina Blue. With nice gloss on this distinctive paint, it recalls feelings of those days when you saw your first Camaro. This is the model that truly started the pony car wars.  It ignited something in you, because the styling was more aggressive, but just as affordable as the Mustang.  In fact, this one has a few interesting upgrades like the cowl hood and the D91 bumblebee stripe that looks great coordinating with the white vinyl roof.  These upgrades combine with the iconic Rally wheels, complete factory trim, and bright wraparound bumpers to be a symbol of how the Camaro stole our hearts all those decades ago.

One of the best features of this coupe is revealed when you open the door.  The blue bucket seat interior looks great against the coordinating blue exterior hue.  This is the kind of color that could have only come from the '60s, and we believe all the major components are original.  In fact, the only two pieces that are non-standard are the upgrades like the AM/FM cassette stereo and auxiliary gauge package.  Everything else, from the door panels, to the carpeting, to the steering wheel is quite original, and it feels as deep and blue as an ocean.

The 327 cubic-inch V8 was the heart of the early Camaros, so we love the honest presentation of this one.  With the correct air topper, correct bold orange block paint, correct dual barrel carburetor, and so much more, it really showcases what an authentic classic Camaro V8 is.  In fact, the date code on this block leads us to believe it could be original to the car.  But more than just history, a classic like this was meant to be driven.  That's why it also has great features like the Powerglide automatic transmission and a newer aluminum radiator to keep everything cool.

Complete with owner's manual, this is the kind of Camaro that gets everyone excited.  After all, it's original in the right places, upgraded where you want it, and absolutely distinctive.  So if you're bold enough, it's time to take home a legend.  Call now!

description: Some cars are just unmistakably cool from every angle.  One glance at this 1970 Chevrolet Camaro Baldwin-Motion tribute and you know there have been some serious investments in upgrades.  The distinct paint package, performance V8, four-speed stick, and side pipes all tell you this is the coolest Camaro you can gets your hands on!

Baldwin-Motion is mentioned in the same breath as Yenko or Nickey in the Chevrolet communities.  This hallowed performance car name only produced a handful of originals, which means buying one today will require forgoing a large home, and it'll make you nervous every time it leaves the garage.  So the obvious solution is the Camaro you see here.  This 1970 coupe carries the iconic and unique full striping package that came from ordering your Camaro through Motion Performance via Baldwin Chevrolet. Even those who don't recognize this hallmark will quiver at the large side exhaust pipes, huge cowl hood, and super-slick red paint.  But more than just look the part, everything from the shine of the bumpers, to the full-width spoiler let you know the detail work on this one is cut-above.

The deep, dark interior wants you to know this Camaro immediately gets down to business.  You sit down in modern ProCar bucket seats that hug your body better than anything from the '70s ever could.  Your left hand gets the grippy thin factory-style steering wheel, and your right one may never want to leave the Hurst shifter.  You have all the right gauges, including a SunPro auxiliary trio under the dash.  All of this is designed to get your heart racing even before you twist the key and hear those side pipes roar.

Because these B-M Camaros were all about the monster motor, you'll love showing off the engine bay.  The 350 cubic-inch V8 is dressed to impress with both plenty of shine from the polished components and a bit of dark attitude with the fender walls and air topper.  But what you and the other enthusiasts will love the most is the proper Motion valve covers.  This V8 backs up its powerful looks with performance upgrades such as the bored .60 over kit, Holley four-barrel carburetor, Edelbrock intake, and a full header package.  The coupe makes all the right muscle car growls, and you're in complete control of this sound and fury thanks to the four-speed manual transmission.  This is a muscle machine made to go hit the road with great features like thick sway bars front & rear, power steering, front disc brakes, and BF Goodrich T/As on proper Z-28 style wheels.

Your heart will skip a beat every time the ferocious exhaust fires up in your garage.  This Camaro comes with all the admiration of a hallowed classic American muscle nameplate, and more importantly, there's no stress when you want to go out and have a little fun.  Don't miss out on this total package classic, call today!
